00:15:57.679 --> 00:16:01.679
of value out of that. But you will get emotionally involved if you start making these apps. You will

00:16:02.320 --> 00:16:06.080
want it to run. You want it to look pretty. You want it to look a certain way, and then you want

00:16:06.080 --> 00:16:09.280
to share it with the world. You will eventually probably want to deploy it, but there are ways

00:16:09.280 --> 00:16:16.479
to do that. I think that's the end. I want to thank all of you. I want to thank my managers

00:16:16.479 --> 00:16:18.880
at Carmex for helping me come out here, and I'm happy to take a few questions.

00:16:19.200 --> 00:16:25.520
And that is the QR code to my talk notes. It's like a little blog post I wrote. It has links

00:16:25.520 --> 00:16:30.159
to all the official documentation. It has links to all the demo repositories. It has links to the

00:16:30.159 --> 00:16:35.840
live apps that I've deployed, and I'm on the Discord if people want to tag me in the Python

00:16:35.840 --> 00:16:40.719
channel or anywhere else. I'm happy to take a few questions if we have any. We have some questions

00:16:40.719 --> 00:16:47.520
for Marcos. The first question is for app layouts in Dash. Is there a way to refactor the layout

00:16:47.520 --> 00:16:52.479
into a class or functions to make it more readable and modular, I guess? That's a good

00:16:52.479 --> 00:16:57.520
question. A lot of people, when Dash apps get more complicated, they break it out into a separate

00:16:57.520 --> 00:17:02.880
file and import it into the main file so it doesn't pollute your one big file. You can also

00:17:03.679 --> 00:17:08.479
break it out into sub, not function, but sub variables. That's what I usually do when I write

00:17:08.479 --> 00:17:14.400
a Dash layout. I'll have variable equals this is the output page, and I'll make that a variable,

00:17:14.400 --> 00:17:18.000
and this is the input section. I'll make that a variable. That helps clean it up a little bit

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:22.800
so that it's a little easier to follow instead of one big block of nested Python lists and stuff.

00:17:24.560 --> 00:17:31.280
Next question is, what's the best way for a Python developer to learn enough CSS to be dangerous?

00:17:31.280 --> 00:17:36.800
That is a great question. I tend to steal other people's CSS, is usually my advice,

00:17:37.760 --> 00:17:42.719
so that every one of these frameworks lets you sprinkle in CSS a little differently.

00:17:42.719 --> 00:17:47.439
Dash has these Python dictionaries that match the keywords. I think Shiny, you put the whole

00:17:47.439 --> 00:17:54.239
CSS string in there. CSS is always an adventure. I think I've tried to get one of these things

00:17:54.239 --> 00:17:57.839
centered. It took me a lot longer than it should have. I'm always Googling CSS. It is always a

00:17:57.839 --> 00:18:00.319
challenge. Like I said, you get emotionally involved. You're like, I want this to be

00:18:00.319 --> 00:18:03.760
centered, and then you spend a lot of time trying to figure out the CSS to get it centered.

00:18:03.760 --> 00:18:09.280
Okay. Let's thank Marcos for a great talk.

